no. i mean can the leader sometimes be followed by two keys instead of one
Yes, you can absolutely do that by nesting submaps. In the world of window managers, this is known as "chained" or "sequential" keybindings.
To do Leader -> s -> a, you essentially create a breadcrumb trail of submaps. Each keypress takes you one level deeper until you trigger the command.
Here is the logic for your config:
nix
# 1. Main 'Leader' key (e.g., Super + Space) enters the first level
bind = $mainMod, SPACE, submap, leader

submap = leader
# 2. Pressing 's' here enters the SECOND level (screenshot mode)
bind = , S, submap, screenshot_keys
# Escape to cancel everything
bind = , escape, submap, reset
submap = reset

# 3. Define the second level (The 'S' branch)
submap = screenshot_keys
# 'a' triggers the area screenshot and resets back to normal
bind = , A, exec, grimblast --freeze copy area
bind = , A, submap, reset

# 's' triggers the full screen and resets
bind = , S, exec, grimblast --freeze copy screen
bind = , S, submap, reset

# Escape to cancel
bind = , escape, submap, reset
submap = reset
Use code with caution.
Why this works:
The "Leader" (Super+Space): Puts the keyboard into a state where it's waiting for a category (like s for screenshots, o for open, w for window).
The "Category" (s): Puts the keyboard into a specific state for that action.
The "Action" (a or s): Executes the terminal command and immediately resets the submap so your keyboard goes back to typing normally.
The "Studly" Warning:
The only downside to deep nesting is feedback. If you get three levels deep and forget where you are, your keyboard will feel "broken" because it's only listening for those specific submap keys.
To prevent this, most people keep a bind = , escape, submap, reset in every submap, so you always have a "panic button" to get back to your normal keyboard.
