when it comes to a screenshot, you can't really have a menu to select eg whether to screenshot a region or active window or whole screen, because then the menu would appear in the screenshot. is that correct, or would it have gone by then?
That is a very sharp observation. You are mostly correct, but it depends entirely on how you trigger the capture.
Here is the breakdown of why Rofi can be a "ghost" in your screenshots and how the "studly" way solves it.
1. The "Race Condition" (The Problem)
If you use a Rofi menu to select "Screenshot Area," and your script immediately runs grimblast, the Rofi window might still be in the middle of its "close" animation when the screen is captured.
Result: You get a screenshot with a blurry, half-transparent Rofi window blocking your view.
The Hacky Fix: People often add sleep 0.2 to their scripts to give the menu time to vanish, but that feels slow and unoptimized.
2. The Submap Advantage (The Efficiency)
This is exactly why Hyprland Submaps (the "Leader land" we discussed) are superior for screenshots.
Invisible: Submaps aren't a "window." They are just a state of the compositor. There is nothing to hide, so there is zero delay between your keypress and the capture.
Instant: You get the screenshot the exact millisecond you hit the key.
3. The "Grimblast" Special Sauce
If you use grimblast (which is in your screenshot), it has a specific flag designed to solve this: --freeze.
When you run grimblast --freeze copy area, it "freezes" the screen instantly.
Even if a menu was there, you can sometimes use tools like slurp to select a region behind or around it, but the better way is simply to ensure the menu is killed first.
The "Pro" Way to use Rofi for Screenshots
If you really want a menu (because you have 10 different screenshot options and don't want to memorize them), you write your script like this:
bash
# Inside your screenshot script
killall rofi && grimblast --freeze copy area
Use code with caution.
By explicitly calling killall rofi before the screenshot tool starts, you ensure the menu is purged from the desktop's memory before the pixels are grabbed.
Summary: Which is "Studlier"?
Rofi: Good if you want a visual list of options (Region, Window, Screen, Upload to Imgur, etc.).
Submaps: The "Elite" choice. It’s faster, requires no "kill" commands, and keeps your screen 100% clean without any artificial sleep delays.
