# Name the submap with the "hints"
bind = $mainMod, S, submap, 📸 [a]rea | [s]creen | [w]indow
submap = 📸 [a]rea | [s]creen | [w]indow
    bind = , a, exec, grimblast --freeze copy area
    bind = , a, submap, reset
    # ... other binds
submap = reset
Use code with caution.
In your Waybar, the bar will instantly update to show: 📸 [a]rea | [s]creen | [w]indow. It tells you exactly what to press next.
Option 2: The "Keyhints" Popup (The Studliest Way)
If you want something that looks like WhichKey from Neovim (a little window that pops up only when you need it), you can use a tiny, lightweight notification or a "dead-simple" OSD (On-Screen Display).
You can chain a notification to your Leader key:
nix
# When you hit the leader, send a notification that disappears after 2 seconds
bind = $mainMod, S, exec, notify-send -t 2000 "Screenshot Mode" "A: Area\nS: Screen\nW: Window"
bind = $mainMod, S, submap, screenshot

submap = screenshot
    # When you pick an option, kill the notification immediately so it's not in the shot
    bind = , a, exec, killall dunst || killall mako || killall swaync
    bind = , a, exec, grimblast --freeze copy area
    bind = , a, submap, reset
    # ... 
submap = reset
Use code with caution.
Why Option 2 is "Hyper-Efficient":
Passive Learning: After three days, you’ll stop looking at the popup because your fingers will remember.
No Ghosting: Because the command starts with killall [notification-daemon], the hints are wiped from the screen the millisecond you make your choice, ensuring a clean screenshot.
Summary
Submaps provide the speed (no window-manager overhead).
Waybar/Notifications provide the visual cues.
